<DOC><DOCNO> AP880602-0136 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1244EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp 1stLd-Writethru b0476 06-02 0569</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0476,0586</SECOND><NOTE>Eds: Subs final item, datelined WASHINGTON, in AM-Religion Rdp,send June 1 as b0476, to CORRECT name of Bishop Chilstrom.</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. Supreme Court has rejected an appealagainst back taxes and penalties by the Church of Scientology,leaving in place the 1967 revocation of its tax exemption.   The high court declined to review lower court decisionspenalizing the group for tax deficiencies in 1970, 1971 and 1972,holding that large amounts of its monies claimed as tax-exempt wentfor private enrichment of Scientology's late founder L. Ron Hubbardand his wife, Mary Sue Hubbard.   The U.S. Tax Court had ruled that $3.5 million was deposited inSwiss banks through a bogus trust in those years, much of it laterremoved to a safe on a yacht, Apollo, on which the Hubbards hadtaken up residence in the Mediterranean. He died in 1986.   However, the group continues to function, pressing lawsuitsclaiming its ``E-meter'' auditing is religious and exempt fromtaxes levied against its income.</TEXT><DATELINE>LOUISVILLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A new religious prize, the $150,000 LouisvileGrawemeyer Award, has been estalished to honor the world's mostsignificant contributions to religious and spiritual understanding.   Funded by Charles Grawemeyer, it is to be given jointly by theUniversity of Louisville and the Louisville PresbyterianTheological Seminary to recognize ``creative and seminal insightsinto the relationship between human beings and the divine.''   Grawemeyer, a 1934 graduate of the University of Louisville anda member of the seminary's board of directors, previously has setup three other $150,000 international prizes in music, educationand political science.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Concerning Nancy Reagan's reported consulting ofan astrologer, the Rev. Richard J. Neuhaus, a noted Lutheranscholar observes:   ``Astrology, if taken seriously, is a deviation from biblicalauthority. If not taken seriously, it is a dangerous dabbling inthings that ought to be taken seriously.''</TEXT><DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Methodist Church says sexuallyviolent pornography should be legally defined as ``obscene,''removing it from protection of the First Admentment guarantees offreedom of speech.   At its conference here in early May, the church also said harmis resulting from child pornography and its distributors ``shouldbe prosecuted to the full extent of the law.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Conservative Judaism's placement division forcantors has reaffirmed its commitment to finding positions forcantors regardless of their sex.   The stand came in response to a decision by the all-maleCantorial Assembly not to accept women in its ranks nor place themas cantors, singers in Jewish worship services.   Franklin D. Kreutzer, president of the United Synagogue ofAmerica, said the cantor's assembly's position was contrary to thatof the Jewish Theological Seminary of America, which trains womenas cantors.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Protestant and Roman Catholic officials arecalling for comprehensive sanctions against South Africa as a wayof supporting forces seeking to change the country's apartheidpolicies of racial separation.   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, head of the Evangelical LutheranChurch in America, told a U.S. Senate subcommitte that ``virtuallyall other peaceful means of persuading the stubborn South Africangovernment to change have been tried, except comprehsnivesanctions.''   Roman Catholic Auxiliary Bishop Emerson J. Moore of New Yorktold the subcommittee that the Catholic Church throughout the worldis ``united in its profound moral opposition to apartheid.''</TEXT></DOC>